{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646466"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:32:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:32:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18186"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18186"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.74,0.03,0.06,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78412"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10900"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18186"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63774"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7220"},{"type":"tags","id":"7236"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25350"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78412"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of pain radiating from her lower back to her right leg. She describes the pain as sharp and shooting, particularly when sitting or bending forward. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. On neurological examination there is weakness in dorsiflexion of the right foot and decreased sensation over the dorsum of the right foot.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following major branches of the sacral plexus is most likely involved in this patient\u0027s symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior gluteal nerve","Sciatic nerve","Pudendal nerve","Inferior gluteal nerve","Posterior femoral cutaneous nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms are consistent with sciatic nerve involvement, which is the largest branch of the sacral plexus. The sciatic nerve is responsible for motor and sensory innervation to the posterior thigh, most of the lower leg, and the entire foot. The weakness in dorsiflexion and decreased sensation over the dorsum of the foot suggest involvement of the common fibular (peroneal) division of the sciatic nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior gluteal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the gluteus medius, gluteus minimus, and tensor fasciae latae muscles, and is not typically associated with the symptoms described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPudendal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory and motor innervation to the perineum and is not involved in lower limb symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior gluteal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the gluteus maximus muscle and is not associated with the symptoms of lower limb weakness or sensory changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior femoral cutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the skin of the posterior thigh and does not affect motor function or sensation in the lower leg or foot.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sacral plexus is a network of nerves that provides motor and sensory nerves for the posterior thigh, most of the lower leg, the entire foot, and part of the pelvis.","The sciatic nerve is the largest branch of the sacral plexus and is composed of the tibial and common fibular (peroneal) divisions.","The superior gluteal nerve arises from the L4-S1 nerve roots, not L5-S2."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63774"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18186"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63774"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T17:24:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T17:25:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10900"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78412"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}